While it _is_ possible to define implicit / explicit conversion operators as static `op_implicit` and `op_explicit` methods, they are currently subject to the same rules as _regular_ methods, which means that you can define only _one_ conversion operator per operator type and  input type.

That is, trying to define a second conversion operator with a different target type is interpreted the same way as a regular method, which results in the same error message you'd get if you tried to define a method overload that differs by return type only (which isn't permitted).

# Steps to reproduce

```powershell
& {
  class Foo {

    # Implicit conversion to [int]
    static [int] op_Implicit([Foo] $Instance) {
      return 42
    }

    # Implicit conversion to [long]
    static [long] op_Implicit([Foo] $Instance) {
        return 666l
    }

  }
  1 + [Foo]::new()
} | Should -Be 42
```

# Expected behavior

The test should succeed.

# Actual behavior

The test fails with `The member 'op_Implicit' is already defined.`

# Environment data


```none
Windows PowerShell v5.1 / PowerShell Core 6.2.0
```

# Support Question

I have a somewhat unusual problem. In [PSKoans](https://github.com/vexx32/pskoans), I need to define a type such that no matter what you try to compare it to, the result is always `$false`. This is needed to be a blank placeholder that _always_ fails Pester tests with comparisons against various items.

Initially, my attempt looked like this:

```powershell
class Blank {
    [string] ToString() {
        return $null
    }

    static [bool] op_Equality([Blank] $self, [object] $other) {
        return $false
    }

    static [bool] op_Inequality([Blank] $self, [object] $other) {
        return $true
    }

    static [bool] op_Explicit([Blank] $Instance) {
        return $false
    }

    static [bool] op_Implicit([Blank] $Instance) {
        return $false
    }
}
```

This works for most things, but has a pretty glaring issue. The comparison `$true -eq [Blank]::new()` returns `$true`. As a result, a Pester assertion such as `[Blank]::new() | Should -BeTrue` _passes_, when it shouldn't. 

A quick second attempt using a C# struct inlined with Add-Type looks like this:

```powershell
Add-Type -TypeDefinition @"
public struct Blank
{
    public static implicit operator bool(Blank item) => false;

    public static bool operator ==(Blank item, object other) => false;

    public static bool operator !=(Blank item, object other) => false;

    public override bool Equals(object o) => false;

    public override int GetHashCode()
    {
        return 0;
    }
}
"@
```

This exhibits the same issue.

Is there a way that I can define such a type in PowerShell or in C# that will function as desired within PowerShell?
